<p style="text-align:justify;">here and there, but could not always be followed in the burnt plains &#8211;we therefore were obliged to abandon the pursuit and gave them up as lost.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">We proceeded on our journey &#8211; arriving within sight of the Mississouri, the Natives flew in crowds to meet us, wishing us joy and congratulating themselves upon our appearance as traders amongst them &#8211; these were of the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">gros Ventres</span> Nation.  Here we found four of the Hudson's Bay Company's Servants like ourselves on a trading expedition.  They had arrived six days before &#8211; and informed us that having lost their way they had fallen in with a party of Assiniboines, who detained them prisoners for seven days, and compelled them to pay handsomely for their liberty</p>

